\section{Computing ${\operatorname{HTP}}(R)$ from ${\operatorname{HTP}}({\mathbb{Q}})$ for a semilocal ring $R \subseteq {\mathbb{Q}}$}
\label{sec:semilocal}

We begin with results necessary to show that ${\operatorname{HTP}}(R) \leq_T {\operatorname{HTP}}({\mathbb{Q}})$ for all rings $R \subseteq {\mathbb{Q}}$.

\begin{prop}[\cite{Sh5}, {Theorem~4.2}]
\label{P: nonzero}
  Let $R$ be any subring of ${\mathbb{Q}}$.  Then the set of non-zero elements
  of $R$ is existentially definable over $R$.
\end{prop}
This proposition  implies:
\begin{corollary}
\label{cor:RQ}
For every ring $R \subset {\mathbb{Q}}$, we have that ${\operatorname{HTP}}({\mathbb{Q}}) \leq_T {\operatorname{HTP}}(R)$. 
\end{corollary}
\begin{proof}
  Every element of ${\mathbb{Q}}$ can be written
  as a ratio $x/y$ with $x,y \in R, y \not=0$.  Thus we can replace all the
  variables ranging over ${\mathbb{Q}}$ by quotients of variables ranging over
  $R$ and add equations stipulating that the denominators are not
  zero using Proposition~\ref{P: nonzero}.
\end{proof}


In a similar fashion one can show that the following corollary is true
as well.
\begin{corollary}
\label{relativized}
For every ring $R \subset {\mathbb{Q}}$, every $m>0$, and every set $A \subset {\mathbb{Q}}^m$
diophantine over ${\mathbb{Q}}$, the set $A \cap R^m$ is diophantine over $R$.
\end{corollary}



This corollary will be used in this section to prove that
an oracle for ${\operatorname{HTP}}({\mathbb Z}[{\mathcal M}^{-1}])$ also gives an oracle for ${\operatorname{HTP}}({\mathbb Z}[({\mathcal M}-{\mathcal P}_0)^{-1}])$,
for any finite
set of primes ${\mathcal P}_0 \subseteq {\mathcal M}$ (Corollary~\ref{corollary:uniformsemilocal}).


Now, we give an effective version of Julia Robinson's
result concerning the diophantine definition of elements in ${\mathbb{Q}}$ that
are integral at a finite set of primes. This lets us decide from an
${\operatorname{HTP}}({\mathbb{Q}})$-oracle whether polynomials have solutions in certain semilocal rings
${\mathbb Z}[({\mathcal P}-{\{p_1, \ldots, p_n\}})^{-1}]$.  We show that the following result is true:

\begin{prop}
\label{proposition:uniformsemilocal}
Let ${\mathcal P}_0 = \{p_1, \ldots, p_n\}$ be any finite set of primes. Then
${\operatorname{HTP}}({\mathbb Z}[({\mathcal P}-{\mathcal P}_0)^{-1}])$ is computable uniformly in
${\operatorname{HTP}}({\mathbb{Q}})$ in the following sense: there exists an algorithm, using ${\operatorname{HTP}}({\mathbb{Q}})$ as an oracle,
that can decide, given any such ${\mathcal P}_0$, whether any given polynomial with coefficients
in ${\mathbb{Q}}$ has a solution in ${\mathbb Z}[({\mathcal P}-{\mathcal P}_0)^{-1}]$.
\end{prop}



